@Node "What is it?" "AGetty.guide/What is it?"
@Next "Features"
@Prev "Legal Stuff"
@Toc "Main"

What is it?
===========

    AGetty is similar to the well-known Getty included in Matt Dillon's
AmigaUUCP package. It hangs on the specified serial port (serial.device
unit 0 by default) waiting for connections via the connected modem.
Once a connection is detected, AGetty provides a @{b}Login:@{ub} request to the
caller.

    Getty disconnects any caller who cannot provide a legal login and
Password within 60 seconds. It also allows only 3 login attempts before
disconnecting. Any attempt to login with an illegal password will be
written to the logfile.

    Upon receiving a legal Login and Password, verified via the
@{b}passwd@{ub}-file, AGetty will execute a specified program, usually
UUCICO or PMail, and stay off the line until the program returns.
Then, AGetty will disconnect the caller and reset the modem, returning
to its original state.


@EndNode

@Node "Features" "AGetty.guide/Features"
@Next "The Modem"
@Prev "What is it?"
@Toc "Main"

Why should I use this Getty instead of the original?
====================================================

    AGetty and Getty do absolutely the same thing, so why should you use
this new version? The question is easy to answer: Because the original
Getty is totally outdated.

This Getty:

   - provides the devicelocking machanism supported by all the major
     terminal programs such as VLT, Term, X-Comm and Terminus, to name a
     few.

   - is completely localized when Workbench v2.1 is installed

   - is pure and can be made resident. This saves valuable memory on
     systems serving several lines, because every AGetty-task uses the
     same code.

   - supports the new features of OS 2.04, like user-friendly command
     line-help, quick-io, etc...

   - uses the @{b}PIPE:@{ub} device of the OS instead of @{b}FIFO:@{ub}

   - is about 20kbyte smaller than the old one and needs less than
     4kbyte stack and only 20kbyte memory during operation.

   - draws your attention to logins rejected because an incorrect
     password was specified.

   - has the ability to loan the used modem-port to another program that
     supports the OwnDevUnit.Library.

   - recognizes incoming calls by the "RING"-message returned by the
     modem instead of relying on the modem-autoanswer. This reduces the
     probability of failed calls that used to occur when the old Getty
     was busy while the modem made the connect. ;-)

   - allows to store login-informations (like username or realname) into
     local shell variables, what is required by certain scripts or
     applications like Taylor UUCP.

   - is written by me (save the best for last)!


@EndNode

@Node "The Modem" "AGetty.guide/The Modem"
@Next "Installation"
@Prev "Features"
@Toc "Main"

The Modem
=========

    AGetty works only with hayes compatible modems, which understand the
AT-command set. AGetty uses locked DTR-rate and RTS/CTS-handshaking all
the time. I didn't find it necessary to make this configurable, but if
I get some responses complaining about this, I'll add a switch to the
config-file.

    The modem is expected to return strings (eg. "OK", "ERROR", "NO
CARRIER"), not errorcodes. The modem's auto-answer has to be disabled.


@EndNode

@Node "Installation" "AGetty.guide/Installation"
@Next "Commandline Usage"
@Prev "The Modem"
@Toc "Main"

Installation
============

    The installation of AGetty is quiet easy: Let's say, you unpacked
the archive in your ram disk. Now copy all files in
@{b}RAM:AssemblerGetty/libs/@{ub} to your @{b}LIBS:@{ub}-directory.  (1) Then copy the
@{b}RAM:c/AGetty@{ub}-executable somewhere in your commandpath, usually @{b}UUCP:c@{ub}
or @{b}UUCPC:@{ub}.

    AGetty may be made resident using the shell-command @{b}resident@{ub}.  (2)

    The advantage of making AGetty resident is that AGetty is loaded
once into memory and can then be used by several tasks at the same time.

    The file @{b}RAM:lib/AGetty.config@{ub} has to be copied into a directory
pointed at by a @{b}UULIB:@{ub} assign. The other files in the
@{b}RAM:lib/@{ub}-directory may be copied anywhere (their paths are
specified in the config file). Usually they go to @{b}UULIB:@{ub}, too.

    If you have Workbench 2.1 or later installed, copy the contents of
the @{b}RAM:catalogs/@{ub}-directory to @{b}LOCALE:@{ub} to localize AGetty.  (3)

    ---------- Footnotes ----------

    (1)  You should call @{b}avail flush@{ub} or even better reset your Amiga to
make sure older versions of the libraries are flushed.

    (2)  Depending on how your un-archiver is configured, the PURE-flag
may not be set on the file. You can do this with the CLI command
@{b}protect AGetty +p@{ub}.

    (3)  Please consult your DOS-manual for further information.


@EndNode

@Node "Commandline Usage" "AGetty.guide/Commandline Usage"
@Next "Configuration"
@Prev "Installation"
@Toc "Main"

Commandline Usage
=================

    AGetty recognizes several command line options, but if you edit the
config file correctly you won't need any to start it. (These options are
meant for machines with more than one port, running several AGetties.
Using the commandline parameters, so you can start each AGetty with
it's own options, without changing the config file every time.) Start
AGetty with @{b}?@{ub} to get the following template:

    [DEVICE] [UNIT/N] [BAUD/N] [-MI=MODEMINIT] [-AC=ANSWERCOMMAND]

        [-LIT=LOGINTEXT] [PRI/N] [-A=ANSWER/S] [-S=SINGLERUN/S]

                       [-H=HARDWIRE/S] [QUIT/S]

@{b}DEVICE@{ub}
     Here you can specify the device AGetty should use to "talk" to the
     modem. This is useful for owners of multiport serial boards which
     need a special version of the serial.device.  If you leave this
     entry out, serial.device will be used by default.

@{b}UNIT/N@{ub}
     This is the device's unit to use. Default is unit 0.

@{b}BAUD/N@{ub}
     This is the baudrate that should be used to talk to the modem.
     You should specify the baudrate here or in the config file (see
     @{"Configuration" Link "Configuration"}) for correct functioning.

@{b}-MI=MODEMINIT@{ub}
     This is the string/command that should be used to initialize the
     modem. The string must be terminated with a @{b}\r@{ub}-sequence, what
     means that AGetty sends the command to the modem and waits for
     response. If anything different from "OK" arrives, AGetty returns
     with an error.

     You may even supply whole command sequences to the modem,
     inserting @{b}\r@{ub} after every single command. Example:

          @{b}ATZ\rATS0=0\rATX7\r@{ub}

     @{i}IMPORTANT:@{ui} AGetty uses its own method to determine a caller, so
     you have to disable the modem's auto answer (@{b}ATS0=0@{ub}).  Otherwise
     AGetty will @{i}not@{ui} work correctly.

@{b}-AC=ANSWERCOMMAND@{ub}
     Here you can supply a commandstring that should be used to answer
     the incomming call. In spite of @{b}MODEMINIT@{ub}, this entry doesn't
     support and though doesn't need to be closed with a @{b}\r@{ub}, AGetty
     appends the return himself.

     The default command is @{b}ATA@{ub}.

@{b}-LIT=LOGINTEXT@{ub}
     Here you can specify a textfile that should be displayed to every
     caller. This is somewhat useless for UUCP sites, because programs
     like UUCico or PMail don't care much about this "welcome text".
     However, a human caller may get your number accidently and you
     want to inform him that here isn't anything interesting available.

@{b}PRI/N@{ub}
     Using this parameter you may change the priority AGetty will run
     at. Usually you should choose a priority above 0, but not higher
     than 5. Let's say about 4, okay? :-) The default value is 0.

@{b}-A=ANSWER/S@{ub}
     If you add this keyword to the commandline, AGetty answers to an
     existent or non-existent caller immediatly without checking for a
     "RING" message from the modem. This switch is useful for sites that
     do not run 24h a day, but rather only for exchanging some programs
     at special times (like mine).

     One example: You talk to a friend of yours who tells you something
     about a program he found on a bbs a few minutes ago. You both have
     your modem and phone connected to the same line. Just execute
     @{b}AGetty -A@{ub} and he starts his UUCICO/PMail using @{b}ATD@{ub} as his
     dialstring and now you can exchange the archive without calling
     each other again. After the mailers have transferred the archive
     you may even go voice again.

@{b}-S=SINGLERUN/S@{ub}
     This switch must be used together with ANSWER or it will have no
     effect. If you specify SINGLERUN, AGetty returns immediatly after
     processing one connection.

@{b}HARDWIRE/S@{ub}
     Using this switch you can tell AGetty that this port is connected
     to another machine using a nullmodem. This means that AGetty won't
     send any modem commands and does not expect a carrier on that line.

@{b}QUIT/S@{ub}
     If you add this keyword to the commandline, AGetty will look for an
     AGetty beeing on job for this line and will signal him to quit.
     This AGetty will terminate as soon as possible, but will complete
     any running login before. If no AGetty for this device and unit is
     working, nothing will happen.

     Another way to terminate AGetty is to send him a CTRL/D break.


@EndNode

@Node "Configuration" "AGetty.guide/Configuration"
@Next "Setting up a site"
@Prev "Commandline Usage"
@Toc "Main"

Configuration
=============

    Let's begin with the easiest part of the configuration: Load the
file @{b}UULIB:Getty-Header@{ub} into your favourite editor and write a nice
message that will be displayed to any (human) caller. (Of course, you
may keep my message but then the shareware fee rises. :->)

    Now take a look at @{b}UULIB:AGetty.config@{ub}. In most cases you can keep
the actual value/string for correct working. Keywords are recognized
only when they're placed in the first column. Comment lines must begin
with a '#' or ';'. Comments after a keyword are not allowed. The
parameter may contain spaces, but it may not end with a space. Leading
and trailing blanks are not parsed by AGetty.

Here's a description of all keywords known to AGetty:

@{b}STANDARDDEVICE@{ub}
     This is the device that AGetty should use as default.  This
     selection is overridden by the command line. Default is
     serial.device.

@{b}STANDARDBAUD@{ub}
     Baud rate to talk to the modem at. Overridden by the command line.
     This entry must be specified!! No default value is provided.

@{b}MODEMINIT@{ub}
     The string to initialize the modem. For a brief descrption of how
     to provide modem commands, please look at the corresponding entry
     in the commandline sction of the manual.

     @{i}IMPORTANT:@{ui} AGetty uses its own method to detect calls! You MUST
     have auto answer disabled (@{b}ATS0=0@{ub}).

@{b}BRUTEFORCE@{ub}
     "yes" or "no" may follow. This entry decides whether AGetty should
     wait for the device to become free or should return with an error
     after 5 seconds. Be careful with "yes": AGetty won't return before
     the device is freed and can not be interrupted with CTRL-C.

@{b}IMMEDIATEANSWER@{ub}
     AGetty doesn't use the auto-answer mode of the modem but his own
     system of recognizing incomming calls. Do you want to AGetty to
     answer the phone immediatly or would you prefer him waiting for
     the second ring? The latter reduces the chance of AGetty answering
     the phone unnecessarily.

@{b}ANSWERCOMMAND@{ub}
     Here you can provide the default modem command, that should be
     used to answer incomming calls. This selection is overridden by
     the command line. Default is @{b}ATA@{ub}.

@{b}MYPRI@{ub}
     Here you can specify the prioritity you want AGetty to run at.
     This is overridden by the command line. Default is 0.

@{b}LOGFILE@{ub}
     Here you can specify path and name of your logfile. If you comment
     this entry out, AGetty won't log its activities to a file.

@{b}LOGCONNECT@{ub}
     If you set this switch to "yes", AGetty will log the
     connect-message returned by the modem. This might be useful for
     debugging purposes.  Defaults is "no".

@{b}LOGINTEXT@{ub}
     Here you can specify the path and name of the (text) file that
     should be displayed to callers. This is overridden by the command
     line.

@{b}PASSWD@{ub}
     Here you can specify the name and path of your password file
     (described later). This entry must be specified. No default is
     provided.

@{b}USER@{ub}
@{b}PASSWORD@{ub}
@{b}USERID@{ub}
@{b}GROUPID@{ub}
@{b}FINGER-INFO@{ub}
@{b}HOME-DIR@{ub}
@{b}COMMAND-TO-RUN@{ub}
     For some programs is may be useful if certain informations (like
     the login-name or realname) would be available in scripts via
     DOS-variables. Each of these keywords represents a corresponding
     entry in the passwdfile of the actual caller. Behind these
     keywords you may specify the name of the variable to hold the
     information of the passwdfile.

@{b}DEVICENAME@{ub}
     Here you can set the name of a local shell variable to hold the
     name of the device AGetty uses. If you don't need this
     information, just comment the keyword out.

@{b}DEVICEUNIT@{ub}
     Here you can set the name of a local shell variable to hold the
     number of the device-unit AGetty uses. The number will be stored as
     ASCII-string, not binary! If you don't need this information, just
     comment the keyword out.

@{b}CONNECT@{ub}
     Here you can set the name of a local shell variable to hold the
     exact connect-message returned by the modem. If you don't need this
     information, just comment the keyword out.

@{b}BAUD@{ub}
     Here you can set the name of a local shell variable to hold the
     DTR-rate between computer and modem. The number will be stored as
     ASCII-string, not binary! If you don't need If you don't need this
     information, just comment the keyword out.

     The datas are stored in local DOS-variables, please consult your
     DOS-manual for further information. These variables are set before
     the command is executed by AGetty and are deleted afterwards. The
     former contents are not rescued!


@EndNode

@Node "Setting up a site" "AGetty.guide/Setting up a site"
@Next "Fax support"
@Prev "Configuration"
@Toc "Main"

Setting up a site
=================

    Okay, your AGetty is configured now, but how does it know what to do
when somebody wants to login?? This information is found in the
"Passwd"- file usually found in "GETTY:" or "UULIB:". For each system
you have to add a line to this file using the following syntax:

   User,Password,UserID,GroupID,Finger-Info,Home-Dir,Command-To-Run

    The fields are seperated with commas ',' and may contain blanks--no
need to include them in double quotes.

@{b}User@{ub}
     This is the login-name of this guy. As described later in this
     section, the login-name of somebody needn't necessarily be the
     same as his systemname. The username is limitied up to 32
     characters.

@{b}Password@{ub}
     This is the password used for that login (not case sensitive) The
     password is limited up to 32 chars, too.

     If you specify a single star ("*") as password, AGetty won't ask
     the user for the password but execute the CommandToRun immediatly.
     This feature is useful for sites that run UUCP and a BBS at one
     port. Then the caller could log in with "BBS" or something similar
     and doesn't have to provide a password.

@{b}UserID@{ub}
@{b}GroupID@{ub}
@{b}Finger-Info@{ub}
     These fields are unused in this version of AGetty, but have to
     exist.

@{b}Home-Dir@{ub}
     Here you can provide an AmigaDOS directory-name. AGetty will make
     this directory the current one, before he executes the specified
     command.  This may be important for some tools like AXShell. If no
     home directory is provided, "UUCP:" is used as default.

@{b}Command-To-Run@{ub}
     This is the command that should be started when the user/machine
     has logged in successfully.

     If you preface the command to run with a single star ("*"), AGetty
     will redirect the called programs standard in-/output to the OS 2.x
     pipe and will pipe the received serial characters to the program's
     standard input and the written characters to the serial.device.
     Using this feature it is possible to control a remote shell (like
     AxShell).

    Some examples:

     quax,peti for president,,,,,UUCPC:PMail quax
     quax_uucico,peti for president,,,,RAM:,UUCPC:UUCico <>NIL: -USER quax
     quax_8k,yeah_yeah,,,(Thomas Mildenberger),,PMail quax

    All entries are for the same person or machine, but depending on the
login name different commands are called. Programs like PMail or later
versions of UUCico allow one to specify the machine name of the caller
in the commandline, so you may have different logins but only one
machine name.

    You can interrupt the actual login-attempt by sending a CTRL-C
break to AGetty.

    NOTE: During the login, AGetty ignores any sent unprintable
charater, like ESC, BS or anything similar. Valid characters are:

     !"#$%&'()*+,-./0123456789:;<=>?@ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ[\]^_`
     abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz{|}~ŔÁÂĂÄĹĆÇČÉĘËĚÍÎĎĐŃŇÓÔŐÖŘŮÚŰÜÝŢßŕá
     âăäĺćçčéęëěíîďđńňóôőöřůúűüýţ˙


@EndNode

